5.3.Baselines
Forecasting. We compare CarbonX with two state-of-the-art tools: CarbonCast (Maji et al., 2022a) and EnsembleCI (Yan et al., 2025). While EnsembleCI performs better than CarbonCast on average, CarbonCast has better tail forecasting accuracy (see Table 2). Hence, we include both tools as baselines. We also implement two moving average-based statistical baselines: EWMA (Shenoy and Hanafy, 2024) and AutoARIMA (Seabold and Perktold, 2010).

We could not compare CarbonX with services such as Electricity Maps (Electricity Maps, 2025a) and Watttime (Watttime, 2025), which also provide worldwide forecasts, because their forecasts are proprietary and not public.

Uncertainty Quantification. Li et al. (Li et al., 2024) provide prediction intervals for carbon intensity forecasts. While both our and their works provide the desired coverage, comparing NIW directly is non-trivial, as the interval width depends on the accuracy of the underlying point-value forecasts. Since Li et al. extends CarbonCast, which has a higher accuracy than CarbonX, our NIW will potentially be higher. We keep this comparison as future work.

Importantly, we note that CarbonX‚Äôs modular architecture enables seamless integration of any state-of-the-art methods that can provide narrower intervals with the available CarbonX forecasts.

Imputation. We compare CarbonX‚Äôs zero-shot and fine-tuned imputation performance against three statistical baselines: (1) Naive interpolation, which fills a missing value using the same hour from the nearest available day (in the past or future), (2) Linear interpolation, and (3) Cubic spline interpolation. Linear and cubic spline interpolation are standard statistical baselines that perform well in estimating missing data in time series. The naive approach simulates a realistic operational heuristic often used by practitioners.

